{"id":"1905.04552","submitter":"Constantin Beli","authors":"Constantin-Nicolae Beli","title":"Representations of quadratic lattices over dyadic local fields","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.NT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Given two quadratic lattices $M$ and $N$ over a dyadic local field $F$, i.e.\na finite extension of ${\\mathbb Q}$, we give necessary and sufficient\nconditions such that $M$ represents $N$. Previous results on this problem were\nobtained by O.T. O'Meara in 1958, who solved this problem in the case when the\nbase field $F$ is 2-adic, i.e. a non-ramified extension of ${\\mathbb Q}_2$, and\nby C. Riehm in 1964, who solved the case when $M$ is unimodular. Some notable\nwork on quadratic forms over dyadic local fields, in particular, on\nrepresentations has also been done by Fei Xu.\n  Our result is given in terms of BONGs (bases of norm generators), which is a\nnew way to describe quadratic lattices over dyadic local fields, complimentary\nto the more traditional Jordan splittings. However, they can be easily\ntranslated in the language of Jordan splittings. The use of BONGs is not meant\nto completely replace the Jordan splitting. Neither they make the proofs\nshorter. The study of quadratic lattices over dyadic local fields is well known\nto be very complicated and technical. However, by using BONGs the results can\nbe written in a more compact form and it is easier to make educated guesses on\ngeneral results by extrapolating results in small dimensions.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 11 May 2019 16:54:55 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 30 May 2022 11:37:29 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-05-31"}
